message:
Two engineering students were walking across a university campus when one said, "Where did you get such a great bike?" 
The second engineer replied, "Well, I was walking along yesterday, minding my own business, when a beautiful woman rode up on this bike, threw it to the ground, took off all her clothes and said, "Take what you want." 
The first engineer nodded approvingly and said, "Good choice; the clothes probably wouldn't have fit you anyway."

description: Security is a top priority for Google. We invest a lot in making sure that our services use industry-leading security, like strong HTTPS encryption by default. That means that people using Search, Gmail and Drive, for example, automatically have a secure connection to Google. Beyond our own stuff, we’re also working to make the Internet safer more broadly. A big part of that is making sure that websites people access from Google are secure. For instance, we have created resources to help webmasters prevent and fix security breaches on their sites.

message:
Interview: Digital Radio Politics: Tech cultural and engineering challenges in campaigns

http://radioactivebroadcasting.net/directory/item/952-open-standards-strengthen-political-industry

Last week, after Campaign Tech West, I joined Karen Jagoda, President of the E-Voting institute and host of Digital Politics Radio (Podcast) for a interview.
If you tend to be more oral and aural, this is better than a blog post  

The interview has to ~10min segments. Check them out here:
Or go directly to the audio file @ Digital Politics Radio site

We discussed many of the cultural and engineering challenges campaigns and non-profits face when applying technical assets and resources to their goals.
In the interview, you’ll hear me run my mouth about:
	What does “Tech” mean? What’s the difference between Digital and Tech?
	What is the current tech, or engineering talent landscape look like?
	As technical resources and assets have rapidly shifted from ancillary to strategic, what challenges exist within campaigns and their internal departments that limit us and what an approach to overcoming them can look like.
	What engineering and integration problems are limiting us and what is an approach to overcoming them?
	What’s the history and cause of the formation of the Open Supporter Data Interface (OSDI)?
	 The cleanliness state of multiple siloed datasets in organizations.
name: Open Standards Strengthen Political Industry

However, "It's amazing that entire internet, including big companies like Google and Facebook rely on this tiny OpenSSL foundation, which manages the free encryption library. message:
Oh HeartBleed.  Had you been a vulnerability in SChannel, Windows SSL stack, we'd never hear the end of the recriminations of Microsoft incompetence and how proprietary closed-source is said to fail in just this way.  Open Source ensures that a gazillion eyes see the code and these nasty problems get fixed.  NOT!

This wasn't even a complicated bug.  Letting the incoming payload (controlled by the attacker) determine the bounds of a memory allocation, and then not scrubbing the memory..  

These are the kinds of things that proprietary shops like Google and Microsoft employ processes to weed out.
What kind of fuzzy analyzers are the OSS community running against critical codebases like this?

https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/96db9023b881d7cd9f379b0c154650d6c108e9a3#diff-38dc72994741420e2b6c5ee074941a45R1498

message:
“Do you think of [high-frequency traders] differently than you did before you opened?” someone asked.

“I hate them a lot less than before we started,” Katsuyama said. “This is not their fault. I think most of them have just rationalized that the market is creating the inefficiencies, and they are just capitalizing on them. Really it’s brilliant what they have done within the bounds of the regulation. They are much less of a villain than I thought. The system has let down the investor.”


An Adaptation From ‘Flash Boys: A Wall Street Revolt,’ by Michael Lewis - http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/06/magazine/flash-boys-michael-lewis.html?smid=tw-share&_r=1

description: Target ignored its own alarms—and turned its customers into victims of an epic hack
likes: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'NzczMzIwNDA0', u'before': u'NzczMzIwNDA0'}}, u'data': [{u'id': u'773320404', u'name': u'George V. Reilly'}]}
message:
One interesting missing piece of data.  The article mentions that the FireEye security software flagged the attacker's malware, but Target Security ignored it.  What's missing is how many false-positives the software was generating.  If the real alert was in a sea of false-positives, it's harder to fault the security engineers.

Missed Alarms and 40 Million Stolen Credit Card Numbers: How Target Blew It - http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-03-13/target-missed-alarms-in-epic-hack-of-credit-card-data
name: Missed Alarms and 40 Million Stolen Credit Card Numbers: How Target Blew It

You should see what they do with the 1s.', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32135988', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 4, u'offset': 24, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T05:16:42+0000', u'message': u'I think someone guessed Josh's password and is posting using his account.', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32139273', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T05:20:34+0000', u'message': u'Can you just format the cell(s) as strings, not numbers?  Or use a leading tick mark?', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32139302', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 15, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T05:57:31+0000', u'message': u'Randall Gellens  yes, but that is a huge hassle.  If you are dealing with tens of thousands of records (say voter lists) ZIP codes are often a problem.', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32139482', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T15:40:25+0000', u'message': u'I blame the US govt and Obama, there should be no zipcodes with leading zeroes.', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32143345', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T18:43:17+0000', u'message': u'Isn't there a formatting option to show leading zeros that you can apply to the column containing zip codes?', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32145345', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 13, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T22:09:00+0000', u'message': u'Peter S. Ford Typical Microsoft thinking, 

How many Microsoft technicians does it take to screw in a light bulb?
None, they would just declare darkness the new standard', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32147751', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T22:09:55+0000', u'message': u'and I thought I was being a clever Internet conspiracy theorist ...', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32147763', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T22:59:32+0000', u'message': u'Of course Excel has it:

1. Select the cells which will contain zip codes.
2. Right-click and select "Format Cells...."
3. Click on the "Number" tab.
4. Select "Special" in the type box.
5. Select "Zip Code" or "Zip Code +4," as necessary

There are also pre-defined formats available for phone numbers and Social Security numbers.

Response to petition: RTFM.', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32148421', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'642287378', u'name': u'Cody Anderson'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-15T23:32:28+0000', u'message': u'All I want to do is enter an East Coast zip code without the goddamned ' in front of it. Is that so wrong?', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32148817', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-16T01:36:52+0000', u'message': u'<see above>', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32149988', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 4, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-16T04:12:18+0000', u'message': u'Josh, why is the number of records an issue?  Can you do a select column or something?  Perhaps the files are being created by tools (not manually) and hence changing the format would be a big hassle?  If so, you can edit the raw XML with your own scripts/tools.  (I got really fed up that Excel lacked the ability to do a find/replace using regular expressions, so I wrote a Perl script that did it to the raw XML.)', u'id': u'10152282452426469_32151164', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-03-16T05:09:35+0000', u'message': u'If the spreadsheets need to be created without manual intervention, then a script to change the formatting could be part of that process. description: Chatting in the living room one night, Ron Orr gave his 15-year-old son Andrew a choice: He could stick with the Boy Scouts of America and his mission to become an Eagle Scout, or he could join Trail Life USA — the new Christian-based alternative that excludes openly gay boys.
message:
It's a free country.  I stand in support of those who wish to exercise their freedom to voice and express their bigotry.  At least now I know who to stay away from.
It's great to see a father encourage his boy to join what will ultimately be regarded in history with the same level of respect as the KKK.

http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/02/28/scouts-boys-trail-life/5907815/
name: No longer loyal to Scouts, boys join Trail Life

{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTc=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'757247888', u'name': u'Amy Blumenfield'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-22T23:18:19+0000', u'message': u'I feel the same way, but I decided the Dell 8" wasn't big enough for the traditional Win apps for me. Switched to a Surface Pro + the click keyboard (whatever it's called) (much bigger investment, but totally replaced my personal laptop) & I"m super happy.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843099', u'user_likes': True}, {u'from': {u'id': u'566505193', u'name': u'Nevin Williams'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-22T23:49:00+0000', u'message': u'Wow, that must be SpikedCoolAid 2.0 kicking in.   ;)', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843390', u'user_likes': True}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-22T23:55:18+0000', u'message': u'You close a modern UI app by swiping from the top to bottom. It's one of my favorite gestures, actually....so dramatic! :)

Glad you're enjoying the tablet. I've had my Lenovo Thinkpad 2 for a year now, and I prefer it to any hardware I have (except when speed is an issue). Your tablet has a CPU about twice as fast AND faster memory AND MUCH faster graphics, so those might not be an issue for you.....

Are there any web sites that are so "busy" that browsing them is slow? I have problems with sites that have a lot of motion ads and slideshows.

@Nevin: there are different kinds of KoolAid.....I hear there's one made of apples, in fact.....', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843452', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'566505193', u'name': u'Nevin Williams'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-22T23:59:31+0000', u'message': u'Mine was made in a press trampled by eunuchs.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843491', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:05:24+0000', u'message': u'UNIX?', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843547', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 10, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:06:06+0000', u'message': u'Paul Johns wow thanks!  I had searched, but the links i ended up at said use task manager.  Good to know!', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843559', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:07:26+0000', u'message': u'I agree that the type of UI you suggest would be a good alternative.....', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843574', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:08:39+0000', u'message': u'My current culprit is Stacks, the instapaper client.  It has a habit of sometimes opening up to a blank black screen.  Closing it how you said and restarting it made it work again.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843586', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 14, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'566505193', u'name': u'Nevin Williams'}], u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:09:53+0000', u'message': u'Nevin Williams  No Kool Aid here.  I've been gone from Microsoft for almost 1.5 years.  They said the implant should stop working well before that.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843597', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 15, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'757247888', u'name': u'Amy Blumenfield'}, {u'length': 10, u'offset': 479, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:13:49+0000', u'message': u'Amy Blumenfield  I hear you.  I got the Dell Venue as a cheap way to get into Windows Tablet.  32GB=$250, 64G=$319.

It is quite small and the newer displays dont seem to like DPI scaling very well.  It isn't so much the resolution, it's the DPI.  Text can be small to read.

I'm also eyeing a Surface Pro, but also the Lenovo Mix 2 10"  It's a nice detachable tablet keyboard combo with pointing device.
http://shop.lenovo.com/us/en/tablets/ideatab/miix-series/miix-2-10-inch/

Paul Johns I looked at the Tablet 2, but I'd wait for a refresh on it component-wise.  However, the keyboard I am using is the one for the tablet 2. (See my pics!)', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843658', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:17:01+0000', u'message': u'Microsoft has done a really good job on the tablet (modern UI) side of Windows 8.1--it's elegant, and quite well-designed.

When I bought my tablet a year ago, they were SERIOUSLY behind on modern UI apps; now it's not so bad, at least for major apps. And being able to run legacy Windows apps--not to mention Office--as well really rocks, as does Windows Update, which fixes problems far quicker than waiting for an update for the entire OS (major advantage, actually).

I wish Microsoft would include pinch-to-zoom for the desktop (perhaps with an even simpler gesture to activate it) to allow you to make areas of the screen with small items to touch larger.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843716', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 10, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:30:06+0000', u'message': u'Paul Johns I was able to increase the size of items on my screen.  The UI will tell you that you can't.  But if you click the "one size for all of my displays" (and be sure to turn off syncing those settings to your other devices) then you can change the DPI setting.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843884', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:35:57+0000', u'message': u'I wouldn't buy a TPT2 now either, but they are/were $369 at Egghead, so looks like Lenovo is starting to clear them out.....', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843966', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:38:55+0000', u'message': u'That's not good enough--I don't want everything bigger all the time, only when I want to touch them. The rest of the time they're a good size.', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31843993', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T00:46:33+0000', u'message': u'Well there is the ease of access magnifier...', u'id': u'10152241784371469_31844065', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2014-02-23T05:01:14+0000', u'message': u'Yup... that almost does it, but not easy enough to use for this purpose. message:
I'm really liking my Dell Venue 8 Pro windows tablet.  In the 2 weeks I've had it, I haven't wanted to touch my iPad.  SO much more productive.  and I don't just mean Office.

The Metro apps are pretty sweet.  Most of the big ones I need are there, plus some other neat things.  
With real Windows, if there isn't a metro app (or more likely, I want to do something unusual), I can just swipe windows to get to the desktop and run a real app.

It's nice to have a REAL filesystem.  I can work real files.  I have git repositories local.  I don't have to fight with prickly iOS apps, their Dropbox et al file support, making voodoo  "Open in XYZ app" to edit anything.  IMHO that almost NEVER works.

For those moments walking around "Oooh I should add this little feature, or I know how to fix that bug!"

Ruby on Rails is installed, RubyMine IDE.  

I even  can run the actual Rails server and test  browse to it from my iPhone at the coffee shop.

The Dell fits in my coat pocket (8", those areal inches not AOL inches).  I've even got some tiny and small Bluetooth/keyboard pointer combos.  Love the Lenovo mobile Bluetooth and TrackPoint combo!

Split Screen is super cool too!.  Want to view a link a friend sent in email?  no prob. Clicking it splits the screen between mail and browser.  I can see and work with both at the same time.  When I'm done just swipe to disappear the browser. Same thing in many apps.

 No more double click the iOS home button, then click the mail or source  app to go back to the email.  

Of course, Apple Fanboys can relax.  It is not as perfect as your precious iDevices.

UPDATE:  Paul Johns pointed out that you can close metro apps by swiping from top to bottom and holding.  Nice.
Apple Fanboys - Go pound sand.

HOWEVER.  I really hate when developers try to be *too clever*  PLEASE Microsoft, make a close button/swipe/other mechanism to easily CLOSE an application manually..   Yes the app linger algorithm is very clever and works most of the time.  But that depends on everything working right.  

Not every 3rd party metro  app is perfect and sometimes they crash or get into a wacky state you can't fix without killing the process.
If I could just swipe/select an app in the left vertical app list and then click "Exit" life would be so much simpler.

An escape hatch like a close mechanism would really help.

Since I don't have that, whenever an app goes bad, I have to drop down to desktop mode, launch the task manager and end process.  

Am I missing a close function somewhere?

caption: www.standard.co.uk
description: The last thing anyone told me as I took off from Nairobi in the direction of Mother Russia was that the concert might be cancelled.
likes: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'NzczMzIwNDA0', u'before': u'NzczMzIwNDA0'}}, u'data': [{u'id': u'773320404', u'name': u'George V. Reilly'}]}
message:
Great article from a UK newspaper owner who was with EJ in Russia.  Some TL;DR

Under Russian law, anyone with HIV/Aids should receive free antiretroviral drugs...

Elton asked one of the other people present whether he should boycott Russia. If he should stop coming there, and try to get sportsmen to do the same. To not allow Russian artists to perform elsewhere. For it to become a culture of isolation. He was told: “No. Absolutely not. For one, the gay community might be blamed. The retribution could become worse. Russia shouldn’t be isolated. In this, as with all things, there must be a constant culture of conversation, of engagement, of reaching out.”

http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/evgeny-lebedev-elton-makes-a-stand-in-moscow-9003448.html
name: Evgeny Lebedev: Elton makes a stand in Moscow

This pattern is ultimately a power dynamic.  People who need this to feel good about themselves will engage in this kind of abusive behavior with whatever fuel is at the ready. Not man enough, not fit enough, not smart enough.  It can result in social, professional or domestic abuse.

message:
SOOOOOOOOOOOO TRUE!!!!!!
Go to Seattle.  Chat up a cute boy.  Ask him for his phone number.  You will always get it.  This does not mean he is interested. You only learn that it was a NO when you call/text and see if he ignores you.

In a more brave city like NYC, you'll ask for the number and just get a NO, or a slap if you are extra lucky.

I was raised in NJ, where it's perfectly fine to say NO, even FUCK YOU NO!.  Then after a decade in Seattle of first suffering confusion of maybe-ness and then being brainwashed into Seattle behavior I moved back to NY.  Now I keep catching myself being afraid to say NO when it's OK!!!  arrgghh
name: The Seattle NO

caption: www.slate.com
comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTk=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'736190083', u'name': u'Andrew Deiner'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T02:06:51+0000', u'message': u'Then Rand Paul had the nerve to attack MSNBC for producing bad journalism...', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30317518', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1009638339', u'name': u'Nicolo Stabile'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T02:12:02+0000', u'message': u'The best part is that he plagiarized Wikipedia. Because who reads Wikipedia?', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30317590', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T02:32:21+0000', u'message': u'Oh Josh, you're just one of the 'haters' like Rachel Maddow!   Rand Paul.   What a joke.   He can't even handle a plagarism scandal.   His would be a short lived Presidency.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30317813', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'100000033065156', u'name': u'Bob Blair'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T02:44:03+0000', u'message': u'We all express ideas that aren't original with us.  For some of us, that's all we do.  Paul's errors aren't in being unoriginal, but in being too lazy to rephrase the opinions he repeats.  Given his huge success in parroting lazy political thinking, I'm not surprised he feels unfairly treated.  I also sympathize with Paul's position that he is being held to an unrealistically high standard: he's a politician and should therefore be held to the traditional standards of honesty and integrity of that profession.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30317949', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 2, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T02:53:56+0000', u'message': u'Bob.   I disagree.    I watched this on the Rachel Maddow show and he lifted verbatim, word for word, ideas about 2 movies and the exact comparisons that were made on Wikipedia.   No doubt his staff just cut and pasted it and thought, "Hey, it's only Wikipedia."   Plagarism is essentially stealing one's original writings.  It's theft, which is why the media industry treats it so seriously.    Which is why the conservative Washington times ended Rand Paul's column.   Good for them.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318023', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T02:59:08+0000', u'message': u'But so what do you think about my question?  Are they aware that they are copying, or do they not know that they are doing so?', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318083', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'736190083', u'name': u'Andrew Deiner'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T03:05:34+0000', u'message': u'It could have just been a lazy staffer assuming they'd never get caught.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318167', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T03:08:07+0000', u'message': u'Exactly, it probably was.   But Rand Paul should have come clean and said he had corrected the problem.   He didn't.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318200', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T03:08:44+0000', u'message': u'And yes, Josh, I think they know exactly what they are doing.   They were (are) copying and pasting and assuming they'll never get caught.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318212', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'736190083', u'name': u'Andrew Deiner'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T03:09:20+0000', u'message': u'I'm surprised the Examiner cared.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318222', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 2, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T03:09:28+0000', u'message': u'Like they say, when politicians get caught in a scandal, it's not the scandal that brings them down, it's the coverup afterwards.', u'id': u'10151995363526469_30318226', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'534141648', u'name': u'Scott Wooledge'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-11-07T03:20:24+0000', u'message': u'Well, the latter isn't really plausible with Paul's situation. message:
"...Republicans are setting a precedent which, if followed, would make America ungovernable. Voters have seen fit to give their party control of one arm of government—the House of Representatives—while handing the Democrats the White House and the Senate. If a party with such a modest electoral mandate threatens to shut down government unless the other side repeals a law it does not like, apparently settled legislation will always be vulnerable to repeal by the minority. Washington will be permanently paralysed and America condemned to chronic uncertainty."

http://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21587211-land-free-starting-look-ungovernable-enough-enough-no-way-run-country

message:
The GOP should listen to Reagan.
""Unfortunately, Congress consistently brings the government to the edge of default before facing its responsibility. This brinkmanship threatens the holders of government bonds and those who rely on Social Security and veterans benefits. Interest rates would skyrocket, instability would occur in financial markets, and the federal deficit would soar. The United States has a special responsibility to itself and the world to meet its obligations."

message:
Why do people fail to 'get' Microsoft?
Microsoft does not give up.  Microsoft will invest in a product, over multiple versions, even if the initial versions aren't successful.  They will keep improving the product as long as it takes to be successful as long as the product area is strategic to the company. 
It's called long term thinking...

That's where MY tax dollars are going. :-(', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29420619', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1427233378', u'name': u'Steve Rubio'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T16:18:41+0000', u'message': u'Because once they get their "Socialist" Medicare and Social Security they become greedy and don't want anyone else to get it! ;)', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29421441', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'558939306', u'name': u'Rob Cochran'}, u'like_count': 2, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T16:44:52+0000', u'message': u'When I was in my 20's I was a Republican. Now that I am older, and not nearly as ignorant as I was back then, I am a Democrat.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29421741', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T17:02:51+0000', u'message': u'I mostly blame parenthood. It does weird things to a lot of people.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29421925', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T17:07:28+0000', u'message': u'@Fabio: I don't know how anyone with a brain can be a Republican nowadays, regardless of age.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29421990', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'500991232', u'name': u'Kes Wold'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T17:43:22+0000', u'message': u'the AARP discounted Early Bird membership?', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29422382', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T18:11:25+0000', u'message': u'The AARP is pretty liberal especially by today's standards.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29422679', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T18:27:02+0000', u'message': u'“Show me a young Conservative and I'll show you someone with no heart. Show me an old Liberal and I'll show you someone with no brains.”

― Winston Churchill', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29422846', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}, u'like_count': 3, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T18:38:41+0000', u'message': u'The reality of the Dems and Republicans in the U.S. is that they are two faces on the same coin.  Both "sides" voted for the Iraq war, the Patriot act, the revocation of Glass-Steagal, the lack of regulation on derivatives trading, and most of the bad budget management in the Federal Govt.    The tragedy in the US is that the Fed govt is ruled by the two parties while a solid third of the population identifies itself as independent.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29422978', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'652366003', u'name': u'Doug Sauvage'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T18:46:48+0000', u'message': u'I started out libertarian (foolish youth!) and moved steadily left over the years.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29423067', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T19:01:41+0000', u'message': u'It appears that that quote and similar ones are falsely attributed to Churchill by some cowardly scoundrel wanting to steal Churchill's authority for their (rather nasty) idea.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29423236', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 2, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T19:03:45+0000', u'message': u'Peter, which the two parties do indeed have the things you mention in common, it is simply false to say that they're "two sides of the same coin" because of their many--and significant--differences. If they were both the same, there would be no need for the Republicans to blockade Congress.

The problem with the false meme that the parties are the same is that it plays into the hands of the conservatives by promoting the hatred of government they need to thrive. If it were true, that would be one thing. But it's not.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29423262', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'534023365', u'name': u'Heather Warncke'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 5, u'offset': 7, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T21:06:03+0000', u'message': u'But to Peter's point, look at the current situation--the Dems are suddenly the can't-get-to-war-fast-enough hawks and the Republicans are in places balking at a military strike. I'm absolutely amazed at the place we find ourselves. Mostly, it just proves that pure politics trump any sort of principles or beliefs in D.C.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29424848', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'534023365', u'name': u'Heather Warncke'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T21:08:40+0000', u'message': u'Oh, and the answer I think to your original question is money. I certainly care more and more about keeping mine for myself and my family as I get older. :-)', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29424881', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1215475354', u'name': u'Ron Poggi'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-05T21:56:54+0000', u'message': u'It is true that as you get older you get more insecure which leads to a person becoming greedier as heather pointed out. But I think with age as the body and mind start to deteriorate in many they can't learn new things as they did in the past and distrust the younger generations and become more conservative as a way of clinging on to the past. There is a reason you don't see many 80 year olds heading back to school to further their education.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29425470', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'747879636', u'name': u'Kip McEntire'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-06T00:29:56+0000', u'message': u'I think people tend to become more "conservative" (opposed to change) as they age because it literally becomes harder for them to adjust.  Young minds can learn quickly and adjust to new environments.  As people age, their brains tend to slow down and are not able to adjust nearly as quickly to new knowledge or situations.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29426903', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-06T01:10:21+0000', u'message': u'I would love to see a clear 3 areas where the 2 parties are significantly different, along with evidence that the members actually believe what the party proposes, and that they actually get results along those lines.   For example, the republicans believe in smaller government, yet since Reagan's time they don't vote for smaller government, and the budget keeps climbing - GONG!   The democrats claim they want regulation of the banks, but major bank deregulation that led to disaster occurred under the direction of the goldman sachs kids who worked in the Clinton Administration - GONG!', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29427378', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1215475354', u'name': u'Ron Poggi'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-09-06T01:43:53+0000', u'message': u'Peter is using texas sharpshooter reasoning.  
You picked data to suit your argument, or found a pattern to fit a presumption.
This 'false cause' fallacy is coined after a marksman shooting randomly at barns and then painting bullseye targets around the spot where the most bullet holes appear, making it appear as if he's a really good shot. Clusters naturally appear by chance, but don't necessarily indicate that there is a causal relationship.', u'id': u'10151856682671469_29427769', u'user_likes': False}]}

comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'Mw==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'1304250027', u'name': u'Andrew Fogle'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-08-19T14:03:48+0000', u'message': u'"Mr. Miranda, Mr. Greenwald said, was told that he was being detained under Section 7 of the British Terrorism Act, which allows the authorities to detain someone for up to nine hours for questioning and to conduct a search of personal items, often without a lawyer, to determine possible ties to terrorism." I mean, is anyone outside the hysterical short-circuitings of the right blogosphere really making the case that what the Greenwald underground has been up to constitutes, you know, terrorism?', u'id': u'10151821181191469_29198251', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-08-19T23:40:45+0000', u'message': u'Thats a fair question and with the obvious caveat of us not knowing all of the details I'll say this.  If these guys are running around with *stolen*, *classified* information about how a government's security and antiterrorism mechanisms work, then it's not unreasonable to try to catch them and take it away from them.', u'id': u'10151821181191469_29204679', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1304250027', u'name': u'Andrew Fogle'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-08-20T01:59:12+0000', u'message': u'No doubt on the face of it it's a reasonable thing for a government to do; whether it's a legal or even prudent thing for a government to do with a fairly carefully written anti-terror statue is another thing. If it came out tomorrow that David Miranda was patsying ten pounds of yellow cake for the Syrian resistance I think American liberals would sleep well at night; for now it looks like the transantlantic security state is using East German theories of jurisprudence to deprive a Brazilian twink of his Nintendo. More to come, certainly.', u'id': u'10151821181191469_29206173', u'user_likes': False}]}

message:
TV wars
From: Time Warner Cable
To: subscribers

CBS Corporation, the owner of several TV networks and broadcast TV stations, has made outrageous demands for the right to continue delivering their programming to our customers. As a result, several CBS-owned channels have been removed from your lineup while we continue to negotiate for fair and reasonable terms.

We deeply regret being forced into this position by CBS, but we're prepared to stand by our customers and do what it takes to fight these unreasonable demands.

The affected channels are:
CBS Owned-and-Operated TV stations in the following cities:
Los Angeles: KCBS and KCAL-Ind.
New York: WCBS
Dallas-Ft. Worth: KTVT-CBS and KTXA-Ind.
Boston: WBZ-CBS and WSBK-Ind.
Chicago: WBBM-CBS
Denver: KCNC-CBS
Detroit: WKBD-CW
Pittsburgh: KDKA-CBS and WPCW-CW
Showtime 
The Movie Channel
Flix
Smithsonian Channel

message: Watched this documentary about Wikileaks saga with Josh Cohen last night. I found it to be very "balanced." Which I mean not in the horrible 24 hour news cycle way of everyone with an opinion speaks, but in a though-provoking way. Made me consider there is a lot of demonizing and lionizing going on from both sides of the authoritarian/transparency debate. It's viewed as a great showdown between Asange and Obama, who are merely symbols of political thought. Ultimately, I walked away thinking neither man was a saintly as their supporters think, nor as evil as the detractors say.

I'm surprised they didn't fully test gmail/outlook.  gmail is so popular and the poor support steers people away from outlook and towards gmail's web interface.', u'id': u'10151631687081469_27962475', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'556642634', u'name': u'Ravi Sarma'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-05-17T02:21:25+0000', u'message': u'On my Mac, Drafts never worked well because Apple Mail was saving the draft every few seconds and Gmail was making multiple copies of it at their end... one day upon checking the Drafts folder using the Gmail web interface I found thousands of messages with 10s of copies of each message! I was self-hoted for years and years but ultimately all the SPF and other spam filtering and black/whitelisting became a pain and I moved to Gmail. After these travails, I switched out of Gmail 2-3 years ago to iCloud. Can't do multiple identities etc, but it works predictably.', u'id': u'10151631687081469_27963925', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'556642634', u'name': u'Ravi Sarma'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-05-17T02:33:46+0000', u'message': u'But yeah if it worked in Outlook 2010, MS must have put in some workarounds for Gmail weirdness that did carry over to the newer version.', u'id': u'10151631687081469_27964084', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1246059281', u'name': u'Chris Hamel'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-05-17T02:41:01+0000', u'message': u'What? description: Observer editorial: What is most important now is the integrity and transparency of any investigation into the use of agents such as sarin
message: "Evidence of exposure is one thing, but proving that it was regime forces that fired chemical weapons requires a far more complex casework, requiring not simply identifying traces of toxins, but establishing by whom, when and where the weapons were deployed. That would involve ruling out both the possibility that the agents were released accidentally – for example in a fire – or inadvertently by forces unaware a shell was chemical. There are precedents for both."
name: Syria: we must not rush to judge on chemical arms

caption: amandablumwords.wordpress.com
comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'NQ==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 9, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-03-21T22:32:40+0000', u'message': u'Marc Love', u'id': u'234328876707168_987045', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 3, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-03-21T23:00:30+0000', u'message': u'Great post on the situation. Yes, she could have handled the situation better. But what happened afterwards so outweighs the original offense that I consider it relatively minor in the whole story. It was absurd that Play Haven fired the guy, incredibly disturbing that Adria was subjected to death & rape threats (with a largely "well what did she expect" attitude from other developers), and outrageous that she lost her job as a result. The whole thing really makes me sick to my stomach.', u'id': u'234328876707168_987102', u'user_likes': True}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-03-21T23:08:43+0000', u'message': u'Seems to me that at every step of the way, people opted for extreme measures rather than reasonable behavior. There they go again, those human beings always causing trouble', u'id': u'234328876707168_987124', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-03-21T23:15:11+0000', u'message': u'I do have to say though, that the point when things went off the rails when Adria chose to publicly post the picture rather than handle the situation privately.  Once that happened, there was really no turning back.  The guys shouldnt have said what they said, but at least the one guy was classy about it and apologized.  People are going to make mistakes and that is just reality.  What's more important to me is that when mistakes are brought to someone's attention that they apologize, and/or make amends.  If they don't then they may face consequences.  However, if you don't give someone a chance to make those amends, then there is no opportunity to learn.', u'id': u'234328876707168_987141', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1291842258', u'name': u'Carlo DeCarlo'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2013-03-22T05:20:02+0000', u'message': u'For a second, I thought you were talking about the Cylon attack on Picon. Oops.', u'id': u'234328876707168_987865', u'user_likes': False}]}

caption:
Black Pride honors Black History Month...
We remember Frederick Douglass on this day, February 14th, the date he chose to celebrate his birthday. As like most African Americans born before or during slavery, the exact date and the exact year of Douglass' birth is unknown (on the first page of "Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave", he stated: "I have no accurate knowledge of my age, never having seen any authentic record containing it."). He was an African American social reformer, orator, writer and statesman. After escaping from slavery, he became a leader of the abolitionist movement, gaining note for his dazzling oratory and incisive antislavery writing. He stood as a living counter-example to slaveholders' arguments that slaves did not have the intellectual capacity to function as independent American citizens. Douglass wrote several autobiographies, eloquently describing his experiences in slavery. His first was his 1845 autobiography, "Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave", which became influential in its support for abolition. He wrote two more autobiographies, with his last, "Life and Times of Frederick Douglass", published in 1881 and covering events through and after the Civil War. After the Civil War, Douglass remained active in the United States' struggle to reach its potential as a "land of the free". He also actively supported women's suffrage. Without his approval, he became the first African American nominated for Vice President of the United States as the running mate of Victoria Woodhull on the impracticable and small Equal Rights Party ticket. He held multiple public offices and was a firm believer in the equality of all people, whether black, female, Native American, or recent immigrant. He was famously quoted as saying, "I would unite with anybody to do right and with nobody to do wrong." Douglass also produced several abolitionist newspapers: "The North Star", "Frederick Douglass Weekly", "Frederick Douglass' Paper," "Douglass' Monthly" and "New National Era". The motto of "The North Star" was "Right is of no Sex – Truth is of no Color – God is the Father of us all, and we are all brethren." The abolitionist newspapers were mainly funded by supporters in England, who had sent him five hundred pounds to use as he chose. In 1848, Douglass was the only African American to attend the first women's rights convention, the Seneca Falls Convention. Elizabeth Cady Stanton asked the assembly to pass a resolution asking for women's suffrage. Douglass stood and spoke eloquently in favor stating that "he could not accept the right to vote as a black man if women could not also claim that right". He also suggested that the world would be a better place if women were involved in the political sphere. By the time of the Civil War, Douglass was one of the most famous black men in the country. He and other abolitionists argued that because the aim of the Civil War was to end slavery, African Americans should be allowed to engage in the fight for their freedom. President Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation, which took effect on January 1, 1863, declared the freedom of all slaves in Confederate-held territory. Douglass conferred with President Abraham Lincoln in 1863 on the treatment of black soldiers, and with President Andrew Johnson on the subject of black suffrage. During the U.S. Presidential Election of 1864, Douglass supported John C. Frémont. He was disappointed that President Lincoln did not publicly endorse suffrage for black freedmen. Douglass believed that since African American men were fighting in the American Civil War, they deserved the right to vote. In 1877, Douglass was appointed a United States Marshal. In 1881, he was appointed Recorder of Deeds for the District of Columbia. He was appointed minister-resident and consul-general to the Republic of Haiti (1889–1891). In 1892, the Haitian government appointed Douglass as its commissioner to the Chicago World's Columbian Exposition. Also in 1892, Douglass constructed rental housing for blacks, now known as Douglass Place, in the Fells Point area of Baltimore. The complex was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2003. We shall never forget...

description:
WE WANT JUSTICE FOR BUDDY THE BASSET...Tell the District Attorney and Sheriff's Department know how you feel about - ANDREW DELGADO - and what punishment you feel he should receive after setting his 3 year old bassethound on fire.

Suspect Andrew Delgado was arrested  November 8th 2012 in Camarillo Heights, Los Angeles, and subsequently confessed to the disturbing crime against his family's pet, cops said. 
The 18-year-old California man was behind bars Friday on charges that he killed his family's basset hound by dousing the dog with lighter fluid and setting the pet on fire. 
"During his interview after the arrest, he admitted setting the dog on fire and also told us he was under the influence of drugs at the time," Capt. Don Aguilar with the Ventura County Sheriff's Department told the Daily News. 

Delgado was booked at the Pre-Trial Detention Facility in Ventura with bail set at $35,000. He is scheduled to appear in Ventura County Superior Court on Nov. 13, 2012 at 1:30 p.m. 



NEWS STORIES; 
http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/man-arrested-killing-dog-setting-fire-article-1.1199677 
http://www.vcstar.com/news/2012/nov/09/18-year-old-man-accused-of-setting-familys-dog/ 
http://www.thereporter.com/news/ci_21970829/deputies-say-andrew-delgado-southern-california-torched-family 
http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2012/11/09/camarillo-man-18-arrested-in-death-of-familys-dog/ 
http://www.edhat.com/site/tidbit.cfm?nid=103375 
http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/ventura_county&id=8869844 


INMATE INFORMATION.. 
ANDREW DELGADO 
http://www.vcsd.org/pr-inmate-list.php 
Birthdate- 27th April 1994 
Booking number - 1287520 
Date booked - 8th Nov 2012 

VENTURA COUNTY SHERIFF'S ADMINISTRATION 
http://www.vcsd.org/contact-directory.php 
Office of the Sheriff 
800 South Victoria Avenue 
Ventura, CA 93009 
(805) 654-2380 Sheriff Office 11/08/2012 

We want to thank Basset Hound Rescue Southern California for standing up and being Buddy's voice and seeing that justice is sought in this case. 
http://www.facebook.com/BHRSC

comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTI=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'521606927', u'name': u'William Strickland Hamilton'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T01:54:20+0000', u'message': u'I'm pretty sure the conservative coalition doesn't want to pay for it', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142718', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 3, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:01:58+0000', u'message': u'perhaps if they looked more deeply at the situation, saw the connections, they might see it as a way to keep more gun rights they might pay for it.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142783', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'502335125', u'name': u'Lane Hudson'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:04:27+0000', u'message': u'This is a key part of so many problems in our nation. Tipper Gore was way ahead of our time when she was working to end stigma attached to mental illness.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142805', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1662443447', u'name': u'Julie Goldberg'}, u'like_count': 2, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:04:56+0000', u'message': u'http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/18/health/a-misguided-focus-on-mental-illness-in-gun-control-debate.html?ref=science&_r=0', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142811', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'10717072', u'name': u'James Passey'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:06:02+0000', u'message': u'Agree, and it isn't just mental health. It is addressing the societal issues that cause gun violence. Some of that can be contributed to availability of guns, mental health, and many other factors. Guns are the red herring IMHO.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142824', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 11, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'502335125', u'name': u'Lane Hudson'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:06:12+0000', u'message': u'Lane Hudson agree.  As a community that often suffers a great deal of inflicted illness due to bullying and other behaviors, our own community can do much more', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142826', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 14, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'1662443447', u'name': u'Julie Goldberg'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:14:20+0000', u'message': u'Julie Goldberg On a broad level, that study may be true.  However, when you look at the list of tragedies being recited now (columbine etc) mental illness is cited as a factor.  The combination of illness, ostracizing, bullying or other negative societal behaviors, and the availability of firepower is a set up for these situations.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142894', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1662443447', u'name': u'Julie Goldberg'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:20:47+0000', u'message': u'I agree.  And I do think we need to remove the stigma of dealing with mental illness and get it covered.  I also liked the piece "I am Adam Lanza's Mother" that was making the rounds this weekend.  That said, to reduce mass killings or simply to reduce violence in this country, we need more effective gun control laws (and a cultural change that doesn't glorify violence).  You already get less gun violence in states with more restrictive laws.  I may not want to go hunting, but I'm not going to take away someone's hunting rifle, so long as they're trained in gun safety.  But you don't need a semi-automatic weapon to hunt deer.  And the background checks people go through to buy a gun from a dealer also need to be done at gun shows.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26142955', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 14, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'1662443447', u'name': u'Julie Goldberg'}], u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:26:50+0000', u'message': u'Julie Goldberg Yup.  Both issues (among others) are at play.  It's inappropriate to argue that we need to focus on mental illness or other contributing factors *instead* of gun control laws.  It's equally inappropriate to do vice versa.  My frustration is seeing the seemingly never ending stream of posts, emails and petitions that focus on one issue.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26143031', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:41:34+0000', u'message': u'I totally agree that we need to work on BOTH, as well as changing our violent culture.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26143181', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T02:42:50+0000', u'message': u'http://www.sfgate.com/opinion/openforum/article/I-am-Adam-Lanza-s-mother-4125542.php', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26143188', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-12-19T13:54:40+0000', u'message': u'You don't hear about mass-shootings at banks, outside airports, or near government buildings. Schools should have security or some of the teachers armed and trained. It takes the police 20 minutes to arrive at a scene. We should change the gun laws, but that won't make schools any safer.', u'id': u'10151344532656469_26147557', u'user_likes': False}]}

message: it's great to see all the interest in gun control after the recent tragedies.  However, why hasn't there been more attention to mental illness?  Though guns may be a force multiplier that increases the damage, why aren't we implementing better mental health care so we can spot and stop people before they hurt others or themselves?

Do you guys vote with colored pebbles?  No, wait.  They would have finished toting up those days ago.', u'id': u'487428994611353_5657295', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-11-13T01:47:13+0000', u'message': u'People can only verify signatures at a certain rate. The counting machines only run at a certain rate. Ballots will arrive in the mail after election day.

You can add more people and more machines, but at some point you get diminishing returns for something that doesn't really matter that much.

Most of the counties in the state have ballots outstanding still: http://vote.wa.gov/results/current/Turnout.html', u'id': u'487428994611353_5657326', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'752053666', u'name': u'Dustin Skyywalker'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-11-13T01:58:04+0000', u'message': u'I don't understand the counties that have one or three remainder votes left to be counted and they won't be counted until the 27th.', u'id': u'487428994611353_5657369', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'100000033065156', u'name': u'Bob Blair'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-11-13T02:07:23+0000', u'message': u'The networks may need a third category:  Red states, Blue states, sane states.', u'id': u'487428994611353_5657417', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 2, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2012-11-13T02:12:53+0000', u'message': u'Dustin: I don't know why--perhaps given that there's such a small number they delay counting provisional ballots until just before the deadline to allow others to arrive.

Bob: Our election system is the best in the country. All balloting is handled by mail; ballots are easy to fill in and are easily read by both humans and machines, and we have a paper trail, so we can do recounts to eliminate errors. And the results are available in plenty of time for laws to take effect and for transitions from one official to another.

What's insane is to have people vote with electronic machines that create no paper trail, meaning there's no way to count the ballots if there's an issue, and no way to fix problems if the system is hacked. THAT'S insane.', u'id': u'487428994611353_5657443', u'user_likes': False}]}

caption: social.hero.washingtonunitedformarriage.org
message:
Can't make it to an R74 phone bank?  You can still help.  We need to make them most effective by contacting the right people. Use our social tool to help us identify likely supporters or opponents among your social network.  Think about it, why should we spend $ and precious volunteer time on a persuasion call to a supporter?  If they haven't voted, we'll give them a reminder to vote call.  If someone is an opponent, we'll avoid spending time trying to persuade them.  Log in to the tool and help for 5 mins here:
http://social.hero.washingtonunitedformarriage.org/dashboard
name: Approve R74

caption: secure.qgiv.com
description: I donated to Washington United for Marriage and joined their Raising Millions for Marriage fundraising team, because I want to do all I can to help Washington state defend the Marriage Equality law. Join me.
message: When Referendum 74 is approved, the first day same sex couples will be able to marry in WA State falls on our 35th Anniversary. Our team is in 2nd place – this is worrisome, because we haven’t raised much money. The opponents of Marriage Equality are out-raising us by tens of thousands of dollars; let's raise millions to defend equality. If each of our Facebook friends gives just $10.00 we can raise over $25000.00 to defend equality and make it possible for John and Stuart to get married in December. Please help us make history. Please give what you can and share this on your Facebook page. https://secure.qgiv.com/hobnob/team/9840/
name: Raising Millions for Marriage - Help John and Stuart Get Married

message:
THE FLAG DID NOT FLY ON PRIDE WEEKEND - PLEASE FLY IT FOR MARRIAGE EQUALITY

More than 3000 signatures were reached in 24 hours on Pride Weekend. Space Needle - how about a $50,000.00 Matching Challenge for Marriage Equality. Please join Starbucks, Microsoft, Sub Pop and other local institutions that have made substantial financial contributions to preserve marriage equality in Washington State. Help us raise money to defend our civil rights. Become a corporate supporter of Washington United for Marriage. Stand with us on the right side of history. It's the smart thing to do - it's the right thing to do.
name: Space Needle: Please Raise the Pride Flag for Seattle Pride 2012 - Sign the Petition!

message:
History Lesson:  Etymology of ginker
A low life burn out. Normally seen driving an old Camaro/Firebird covered in primer spots and Led Zepplin booming from the stereo. A chain wallet and a jean jacket is always part of the ginker look. This term may have originated in East Brunswick New Jersey in the 70s.

Allegedly: “Ginker” first appeared in English in the early 1970s as “Gink” referring to any member of the Ginkovitz family of East Brunswick, NJ and later the term evolved to its present form of “Ginker”. 

http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=ginker&defid=1578826

message: So NTFS finally gets symbolic links.  The syntax is mlink linkname target.  On unix the syntax is ln -s target linkname.  AARGH  I already had to constantly check the usage of this with just unix.  Now, i'm going to be completely confused and blow away a few important files I'm sure.  Sometimes it makes sense just do it the way unix does it.

message:
Hey Chicago facebook peeps...

Tonight is a screening of Judas Kiss at Chicago Reeling, the LGBT film festival.  I'm an associate producer of the film.

It's at 9.15pm, at Landmark Century

Description:

	Do you ever wish you could go back and fix the mistakes of your past? In this science fiction drama, a phantasmal blip in time gives failed filmmaker Zachary Wells (Charlie David, Mulligans), a chance to change his destiny when he returns to his alma mater as a judge for their annual student film festival. Set on the verdant campus of fictitious Keystone Summit University, Zach is pulled into a tug of war between his tormented past and troubling future after an anonymous one-night stand with a freshman sets of a course of events that unfold in startling twist and turns.

	http://reelingfilmfestival.org/?page_id=77&event_id=88 

Tickets will be available at the box office.  ($11)
there will be Q&A after the screening with Carlos Pedraza, Writer/Producer, myself and one of the stars.

Check it out of you are looking for something to do tonight
name: reelingfilmfestival.org

caption: wired.com via Zite iPad App
description: When the rich do something to deserve their riches, nobody complains. But when those at the bottom don't understand the unequal distribution of wealth, they get furious. Neuroscience blogger Jonah Lehrer examines the psychological roots of the occupy movement.
message: This monkey wants a grape. "A similar lesson emerges from a classic experiment conducted by Franz de Waals and Sarah Brosnan. The primatologists trained brown capuchin monkeys to give them pebbles in exchange for cucumbers. Almost overnight, a capuchin economy developed, with hungry monkeys harvesting small stones. But the marketplace was disrupted when the scientists got mischievous: instead of giving every monkey a cucumber in exchange for pebbles, they started giving some monkeys a tasty grape instead. (Monkeys prefer grapes to cucumbers.) After witnessing this injustice, the monkeys earning cucumbers went on strike. Some started throwing their cucumbers at the scientists; the vast majority just stopped collecting pebbles. The capuchin economy ground to a halt. The monkeys were willing to forfeit cheap food simply to register their anger at the arbitrary pay scale."

description:
Il y a tellement à voir et à faire à la tour Eiffel ! Flâner au 1er étage, contempler Paris au 2...ème, et faire le plein de sensations au sommet. 

Faites de votre expérience sur la Tour un instant unique à partager entre amis ou en famille !

Retrouvez nos suggestions pour enrichir votre visite sur notre site officiel : http://www.tour-eiffel.fr

Emportez toute la tour Eiffel  dans votre smartphone grâce à notre guide de visite disponible sur :
- l'AppStore : https://itunes.apple.com/fr/app/tour-eiffel-guide-officiel/id484086108
- Google Play : https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=fr.sete.Eiffel_fr

Réservez une table dans l'un des restaurants de la tour Eiffel : http://www.restaurants-toureiffel.com

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

There is so much to see and do at the Eiffel Tower! Wander on the 1st floor, contemplate Paris from the 2nd floor and experience new sensations at the top.

Make your experience on the Tower a unique moment to share with friends and family!

Find our suggestions to enhance your visit on our official website: http://www.tour-eiffel.fr

Take all the Eiffel Tower in your smartphone thanks to our visit guide available at:
- the App Store: https://itunes.apple.com/fr/app/tour-eiffel-guide-officiel/id484086108
- Google Play: https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=fr.sete.Eiffel_fr

Book a table in one of the restaurants of the Eiffel Tower: http://www.restaurants-toureiffel.com See More

likes: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTAwMDAwMjk2MTQ0ODQ0', u'before': u'MTAwMDAwMjk2MTQ0ODQ0'}}, u'data': [{u'id': u'100000296144844', u'name': u'Jared Beckman'}]}
message:
Good stuff for managers. However, having one of the rules in your culture being "Don't be a sissy" using a word that is commonly used to insult gay and other kids is counter-productive. It's a particular word that evokes memories of discrimination

http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/business/13hire.html?_r=1
name: Google’s 8-Point Plan to Help Managers Improve

caption: fosspatents.blogspot.com
description: This blog covers software patent news and issues with a particular focus on the competitiveness of Free and Open Source Software (FOSS).
message:
The cat-fight continues.  In response to Google's claim that they expect to owe zero:  "Fortunately for Oracle, Judge William H. Alsup agreed with Oracle on this point, saying that such a claim would be ridiculous, and that Google is definitely going to pay up "probably in the millions, maybe in the billions" at some point."
Judge to Google lawyer: "'You're going to be on the losing end of this document with Andy Rub
name: FOSS Patents: Oracle gets to depose Google CEO Larry Page for two hours on willful patent infringeme

caption: news.cnet.com
comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'Ng==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'755755144', u'name': u'Lester Waters'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T18:06:16+0000', u'message': u'It doesn't appear the QoS on the network traffic is the fast lane factor. Rather, it is Google's massive connections to the rest of the internet and its ability to replicate content across servers to minimize hop counts when serving up the web pages. Not a bad idea for them to be in the hosting business. MS could do the same... :)', u'id': u'228946070477623_3239302', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'755755144', u'name': u'Lester Waters'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T18:10:51+0000', u'message': u'I might also add that it the service appears to only be suitable for largely static content... So you're typical restaurant web site menu page, etc. Not sure what happens for interactive pages... I suppose you're routed back to the "real" web site (Google acts as a Proxy Server).', u'id': u'228946070477623_3239322', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'692860580', u'name': u'Matt Hargett'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T18:36:54+0000', u'message': u'it's the same as akami-type approach, no? very different from the QoS/DDoS approach of comcast, etc.', u'id': u'228946070477623_3239466', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'517281730', u'name': u'Peter S. Ford'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-29T05:44:18+0000', u'message': u'There are Internet access providers and then there is everyone else.  NetNeu is all about making sure the concepts of "common carriage" apply to access providers.   Analogous to Interstate Commerce Act of 1887 for the railroads.', u'id': u'228946070477623_3242360', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-29T22:50:07+0000', u'message': u'@peter:  Agree.  I dont want the Internet to be like cable tv.  I don't want to be at the mercy of my provider to decide whether or not I can get access to sites/content/channels like Logo.', u'id': u'228946070477623_3246102', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 12, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'692860580', u'name': u'Matt Hargett'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-29T22:54:30+0000', u'message': u'Matt Hargett Similar.  My view is that it is about how much influence and control you have over the medium.  Google has a large amount, but not enough to prevent choices. If they eventually dominate too much, then it could be a problem.', u'id': u'228946070477623_3246120', u'user_likes': False}]}
description: With its new Page Speed Service, Google will rewrite your Web page and host it on its own servers. Unlike previous efforts to speed the Web, this one isn't free. Read this blog post by Stephen Shankland on Deep Tech.
message: Hmm.  So it is NOT OK for Internet backbone providers to cut deals with content providers to have their content served in "the fast lane", but it's OK for Google to do so.
name: Google to speed up, host customers' Web sites
