{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MjU=', u'before': u'MQ=='}, u'next': u'https://graph.facebook.com/v1.0/569966468_226816300693990/comments?access_token=CAACEdEose0cBAPvhcZCRMVkXYCrbdiXUWhfBuA0UMGqXTeV8TF1iwWBJ9SINex3TpkNyw9Vk2kAijxfwlACAi4FUUUPiMQHOxtvmZCsaUkfVG9vHjKmicW0NzBszgCPJNVtGpkwsNqaxhSCjlPOIpjh3BuGZBA6ZAxKObAdTa0qLprnzavfeJDiB1NpheGRkifXmGkkZAoQZDZD&limit=25&after=MjU%3D'}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T00:45:26+0000', u'message': u'Good riddance. Haven't used one in ~3 years.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236838', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T00:51:52+0000', u'message': u'I so rarely use the optical drive on my laptop that I kind of hope they get rid of them on the Pros before I go buy my new one. I'll be glad for the lighter machine.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236860', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T00:52:41+0000', u'message': u'...it's also worth noting that everyone bitched and pissed and moaned when Apple did away with the floppy drive. They led the industry on that one. They're doing the same here.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236868', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T00:57:33+0000', u'message': u'Yup.  the article examines that.  As long as Apple makes decisions that you do like, then there isn't a problem with 'benevolent dictator'.  However when they do, then it isn't.  Inevitably that happens.  A similar thing is going on right with batteries. After Apple made mac batteries non-removable, 3rd party external batteries started showing up.  Now Apple is suing them.  Apple wont let them use the mac connector to make external batteries that plug into the mac.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236884', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T00:59:58+0000', u'message': u'If you're worried about it, don't buy Apple stuff. For those of us who like Apple's products, and think they're making smart decisions, we'll happily remain a year or two ahead of the rest of you.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236890', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:09:47+0000', u'message': u'Hmm.  It seems to me that being "ahead" in this case has more downsides than upsides.  While I could agree that the need for an ODD is trending downward, and that need will eventually fall below the threshold that I don't need one, that is still in the future.  So in the present, while it may please my ego to be "ahead of the rest", my practical side would suffer some degree of pain for not having one when I need it. 

I also like that when I bought my thinkpad, I got to choose what populated the device bay: an extra battery pack, an ODD, an extra HDD, etc.  It's the additional degree of user choice and smaller degree of control I am forced to live under.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236941', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:11:36+0000', u'message': u'I also wouldnt want to live without my docking station.  (another apple no-no).  
That said, I don't have a problem buying apple products for certain categories.  Laptop or Computer, No.  But for a phone or tablet, I'm ok with it.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236954', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:12:05+0000', u'message': u'So glad you approve. :P', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236957', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:14:03+0000', u'message': u'Also... you have choice with Apple products as well. Buy one or don't. My practical side says I almost never use my optical drive now, and when I do it's not the only way to solve the problem. All this griping about products you don't now, and never had any intention of owning. So silly. :P', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236978', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:16:02+0000', u'message': u'This is hardly "benevolent dictator." They've made a product decision. If you want a computer with an optical drive, buy an external one or buy a non-Apple computer. It's not like they're remotely disabling all optical drives in computers people have already purchased.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3236995', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:20:31+0000', u'message': u'Benevolent dictator with Apple is when they do things like change the iPhone Developer Agreement in ways that effect developers' livelihoods after they've already built their business on the iPhone platform. That's a situation where customers (in this case developers) are actually locked in and subject to the whims of Apple.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237031', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:20:39+0000', u'message': u'@Marc: Sure it is.  One company (er, one person) controls the whole hardware ecosystem. Steve Jobs decides what kinds of peripherals you can buy for Mac, whether those are from apple or acme.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237032', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:23:07+0000', u'message': u'@Josh: I think that's a gross exaggeration to say he controls the whole hardware ecosystem. Sure he has a large influence on where it goes because he controls a significant *minority* of the hardware marketplace with his company and makes important decisions and investments regarding what technologies win and lose with Apple. But he doesn't control the whole hardware ecosystem. Optical drives have been on their way out for years now. And you can blame the internet for that, not Steve Jobs.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237047', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:23:16+0000', u'message': u'So, you're telling me Dell doesn't control their whole hardware ecosystem? Everything Dell builds, they make design decisions about. HP, Asus, Acer... That they're all more risk-averse somehow makes them superior to a company that isn't?', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237049', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:24:36+0000', u'message': u'@Adam, sure, there's degrees of lock-in all around.  However, it's the degree not the principle that is what causes pain. In the laptop/desktopserver market, there is a high degree of choice (within the windows world at least).  Mac is much more constrained.  If Dell tells me no more embedded ODD, I can go to a ThinkPad or HP.  If I want to run MacOS, I'm stuck.  I have to make my OS and HW decision together.  I can mix and match in the Windows world.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237058', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 9, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:27:36+0000', u'message': u'Marc Love  When I said "whole" I meant the whole Mac (or MacOS) based ecosystem.  There are no other legal MacOS HW systems except Apple's.  So certainly for the those types of things you are stuck with what Apple decides to build and you can't get a different MacOS machine from Dell or others.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237082', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:28:04+0000', u'message': u'And if that's important to you, you should stay in the Windows world. For many people, though, that's not a shared value, and the benefits of buying an Apple make up for the constraints. For instance, I know when I buy a Mac, it's not going to be loaded with bloatware from the hardware manufacturer that can't be removed without a computer science degree.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237089', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:28:49+0000', u'message': u'...  even worse, Apple's control goes beyond what they themselves build.  I'm fine if they don't want to build an external battery that can connect directly to the Apple magsafe connector.  Fine. 
 But to step in and prevent a third party that wants to meet customer demand by building such a product just because Apple says so?', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237099', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:29:06+0000', u'message': u'@Josh: Apple users have been aware of that situation for years. It's the trade off we chose when chose the platform. Better overall experience in exchange for letting Apple make more decisions and giving us less options. If Apple starts fucking up, people can still make the transition back to PC's. Although granted going back won't be as easy. ;-)', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237103', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:29:06+0000', u'message': u'Fortunately, being stuck with what Apple decides to build usually means top notch product engineering and support.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237104', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:31:12+0000', u'message': u'I'm actually looking forward to not having an optical drive. I think it's a good design decision... it's a choice I'd likely have made a long time ago considering the degree to which I never use my optical drive but still am forced to carry it around (as I would be on just about any OEM Windows laptop).', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237120', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 10, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:31:35+0000', u'message': u'Josh Cohen I thought I might care about that when I made the switch from Microsoft-based systems to OSX-based systems, and in the last 4 years, I have never once felt constrained in my choices. I just don't need that much choice. And the benefits I get from the Apple ecosystem are huge.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237121', u'user_likes': False}, {u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:32:38+0000', u'message': u'Also, Cohen, don't you know by now there's no convincing me once I've made up my mind? ;P', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237128', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:34:00+0000', u'message': u'LOL @ Adam', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237135', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'message_tags': [{u'length': 9, u'offset': 0, u'type': u'user', u'id': u'1296258079', u'name': u'Marc Love'}], u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-07-28T01:34:06+0000', u'message': u'Marc Love You just hit the nail on the head.  It's a trade-off that a lot of people are happy with.  (~10% of the market)   They cede control and enjoy the benefits.  My comment is that the timing of when to move off of a given technology and migrate, such as away from ODD, is not something you can decide on your own.   

The control issue is broader than just MacOS, I'm frustrated by Apple's control in many areas.  
However, for a phone, I've made a similar choice.  When I bought my last phone, I wanted a tool not a science project, so I chose iPhone over Android.', u'id': u'226816300693990_3237137', u'user_likes': False}]}

message: ...and so are you if you live solely in a top to bottom ecosystem that is controlled by a single company.  I don't.
name: Editorial: Apple's officially over the optical drive, for better or worse

comments:
{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'OQ==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'100000033065156', u'name': u'Bob Blair'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T19:20:39+0000', u'message': u'The EETimes story is _much_ more tentative than the winbeta story that is based on it.', u'id': u'106622846092918_57744', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T19:21:22+0000', u'message': u'got a link?  What's your read on it?', u'id': u'106622846092918_57745', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'27318078', u'name': u'Jerame Davis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T19:24:32+0000', u'message': u'They will not be switching to Intel unless Intel. They bought an entire custom chip house last year, why on earth would they switch away from the core competency of the talent they just purchased for millions of dollars?

Also, Intel has yet to produce a chip that comes close to the ARM Cortex, on which the A4/A5 series is based, in terms of performance, cost and power consumption.

So, unless Intel is custom manufacturing chips for Apple - like Samsung is now - this article is just speculation and perhaps some wishful thinking.', u'id': u'106622846092918_57753', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T19:37:16+0000', u'message': u'@jerame agreed.', u'id': u'106622846092918_57777', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'27318078', u'name': u'Jerame Davis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T19:42:32+0000', u'message': u'@Josh - I know Intel really wants that business, so perhaps they planted this piece to generate some buzz and prop up their stock price or something.

I just don't see any logical reason for Apple to switch. You don't fix what isn't broken and the A4/A5 chips are absolutely phenomenal.

I mean, maybe they've hit an engineering roadblock for the A6, but I'm doubtful. Their chip guys are probably just now getting settled in and ramping up to speed on design. The A4 was a custom design before they bought that firm (I can't remember their name right now - grr) and the A5 is the first one any of those engineers even touched.

So, like I said before, I don't see why Apple would spend millions to purchase their talent, then totally change directions. Makes absolutely no sense

But anyone not really up on the ins and outs of this stuff could easily fall for it and buy some Intel stock based on the speculation. Maybe the author has some stock to offload and wants to get a good price.', u'id': u'106622846092918_57789', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'100000033065156', u'name': u'Bob Blair'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T19:49:57+0000', u'message': u'EETimes story: http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4215650/Intel-vying-for-Apple-foundry-business-', u'id': u'106622846092918_57808', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'529413043', u'name': u'Paul Johns'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T20:24:20+0000', u'message': u'"Foundry" means custom-manufactured....', u'id': u'106622846092918_57953', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'100000033065156', u'name': u'Bob Blair'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-03T20:29:09+0000', u'message': u'My take is that Apple doesn't like a single source of supply any better than other IHVs do.  They can get ARMs built anywhere.', u'id': u'106622846092918_57966', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'27318078', u'name': u'Jerame Davis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-05-04T16:33:11+0000', u'message': u'Smartest thing I've read on this whole issue: http://arstechnica.com/business/news/2011/05/intel-to-fab-arm-chips-for-apple-its-possible.ars?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=rss', u'id': u'106622846092918_60870', u'user_likes': False}]}
description: It looks like Apple will be using Intel as a main processor manufacturer to power the iPad, iPod touch, and the iPhone. Apple, who currently uses Samsung, will focus on making a switch to Intel within a year.
message: Will apple continue doing design (as in A4) but have Build them or will they just reuse Intel-built chips?
name: Intel to Build Next Generation Processor for iOS devices? | WinBeta

message: Google does a lot of good things for society and the environment.  These efforts and the "do no evil" mantra has led people to grant them some "benevolent dictator" powers because they perceive that Google is acting for the common good.  However, when they start to contradict their own principles when it is in their interests, things start to slide towards the bad kinds of dictatorship.
name: Google accused of hypocrisy on Grooveshark ban

message:
Due to the Quake, the planetary axis has shifted almost 1 foot, and Japan has moved almost 8 feet.  GPS will need a patch. 
http://news.softpedia.com/news/Japan-Earthquake-Shifts-Earth-s-Axis-189203.shtml

caption: www.infoworld.com
comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'Mg==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-03-09T22:19:40+0000', u'message': u'Tell me your modemular history', u'id': u'115987145142401_330710', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'566505193', u'name': u'Nevin Williams'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-03-09T23:19:26+0000', u'message': u'Lets see....  I started with a 300 baud VICmodem for my VIC20, and ran up a huge compuserve & Dow Jones bill with it... (mostly the former, on chat, go figure).  I would eventually get a C=64 1200 baud modem which sufficed for my basic university VAX connectivity, though the load of running it on my 64's motherboard seemed to cause heat-related intermittent failures, culminating in its SID chip ceasing to function.  For the next school year, I got an Amiga 500, with a no-name 2400 baud modem, which albeit a no-name, was immune to power fluctuations and line-noise that would knock every other modem off of the bank I'd be dialed into. (handy when modem banks were over-subscribed).  I ran with that setup (JRComm and the 2400) for over 2 years, until when asked by several friends what I wanted for my birthday, I asked for a 9600 baud modem, which they all pooled together and got me a fairly decent one, not USR, but whose name escapes me.  I would use this for another 2 or 3 years until 1995 when I went to work for ANS, and they had a few 14.4s kicking around that worked fine with Telix on the IBM pc they'd loaned me (the Amiga remained in Halifax).  By 1996 got a used Acer with a 28.8 internal that Linux Slackware recognized, and continued to use that until '97, when I moved to SF, and my roommate had an ISDN network.  In '99, I bought a house and a fully loaded Gateway, and cable modem service to ISPChannel.  ISPChannel would eventually go out of business, and @Home would serve San Bruno for a year before going tits-up themselves, whereupon I was asked to come in and do a contingency plan for them, which worked out rather well for both of us until my hiring director retired, and the new director and I didn't see eye-to-eye.', u'id': u'115987145142401_330841', u'user_likes': False}]}

message: Ok, I was all good with the United - Continental merger, but this is some serious sh*t!  On a long flight like EWR->SEA, if I'm in coach, I don't even get a bag of pretzels to help cope with this?  Do I still get a diet coke?  What's next?  no floatation seat cushions? Actually, i think i'd prefer the pretzels.  I know how to swim.
name: Airlines Decide to Stop Serving Pretzels

This election was wierd. Nickels got knocked out over the snowpocalypse handling this is what is left. ', u'id': u'180167212024145_2320334', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-28T00:58:31+0000', u'message': u'Nickels got knocked out because the people in the City of Seattle are pretty dumb, short sighted and vengeful.  He got so much stuff done over his years in office.  Yet 1 event, and the media taking advantage of it, and now he's gone.   And Seattle is left with Mayor McMacIntosh.   I wonder if he's going to give a speech at Boeing and talk about the wonders of Airbus.', u'id': u'180167212024145_2326533', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-28T02:26:59+0000', u'message': u'Apparently they aren't unique.  When I got to new york I thought that THAT city would know how to deal with a snowstorm.  Only days later I was proven wrong as the city was clobbered by a snowstorm.  People were so unhappy with the response they were clamoring for the mayor's hide.  New tip for mayors"  Plow your own driveway LAST.', u'id': u'180167212024145_2327008', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-29T01:53:30+0000', u'message': u'New York knows how to deal with snowstorms.  That xmas snow a few weeks ago was an anomoly.  It was right at xmas time, so of course people were on vacation, just like you were.  And I think because it was at xmas, there just wasn't the management staff around to make the right call about how severe it was.  Turn out it was pretty severe.', u'id': u'180167212024145_2334008', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1040370720', u'name': u'Richard Borkowski'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-29T01:55:17+0000', u'message': u'Also, there was a Republican Councilmember who lied about the union staging a slowdown strike.  He's now under investigation.  I guess saying lying Republican is being repetitive.  That's all they can do, is lie.', u'id': u'180167212024145_2334017', u'user_likes': False}]}

comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTY=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'698265965', u'name': u'Markus Young'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T14:24:10+0000', u'message': u'Quite un-inspiring isn't it Josh! ;-)', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4741733', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1073462339', u'name': u'Scott Vanderau'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T16:50:01+0000', u'message': u'As long as Continental gets to run the Airline, I don't care what the logo looks like.  If I ever hear "economy plus" again, I may have to kidney punch someone.', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4742554', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T18:04:46+0000', u'message': u'I completely agree scott.  Continental has had great customer service and elite benefits.  So far, they haven't switched to the United way.  Elite customers get "extra legroom" for free.  Updgrades are automatic if available.', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4743243', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1073462339', u'name': u'Scott Vanderau'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T18:26:11+0000', u'message': u'Yep.  Plus it would be great to get to combine my United and Continental miles.', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4743410', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T19:22:20+0000', u'message': u'that will be cool if you cna add them together.', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4743825', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1073462339', u'name': u'Scott Vanderau'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T20:34:48+0000', u'message': u'i think that's how it's supposed to work?', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4744286', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1389752480', u'name': u'Jishnu Mukerji'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-10T22:13:25+0000', u'message': u'I just came back from Delhi India nonstop to Newark on a Continental 777 in the new United livery - ship #19. Service and food were excellent and those new lie flat seats/beds in Business-First are really nice and cozy.', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4744948', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-11T01:33:09+0000', u'message': u'Is it business or first, and how flat are the lie-flat?  Also, on a 777 is every seat climb-over-or-be-climbed-over?', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4746220', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1455231937', u'name': u'Valerie K Kane'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-11T05:26:18+0000', u'message': u'I can't get "cut and paste" out of my head.  I think Continental has better customer service too.', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4747478', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'608480164', u'name': u'Dan Ager'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-11T06:20:46+0000', u'message': u'No expense spared on that one...the could have just done away with the paint....nope American have that in the bag!', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4747669', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1389752480', u'name': u'Jishnu Mukerji'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-11T12:06:38+0000', u'message': u'@Randall it is J Class so technically business class. Continentl brands them as Business-First, since they do not have international First Class. The lie flats are really flat in the sleeping position and quite comfortable in the sitting position, with all sorts of positions between the two possible', u'id': u'10150121141021469_4748682', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2011-01-11T17:07:27+0000', u'message': u'How flat?  True 180? caption: news.cnet.com
description: As software becomes a constant work in progress, it's time to let its makers bear responsibility for keeping it current. Read this blog post by Stephen Shankland on Deep Tech.
likes: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'NzA5NTIwMjYx', u'before': u'NjIzNjUzMzQ2'}}, u'data': [{u'id': u'623653346', u'name': u'Ted Takvorian'}, {u'id': u'709520261', u'name': u'Michael Davis'}]}
message: Yup.  That's what it takes to maintain a software product.    This is different, as they say than when Microsoft does it.  When Microsoft does it it's just because we have to keep sending updates because we don't know how to write software; our products sux0rz.  In reality, the newcomers will have their fair share of hiccups, breakage, and otherwise bad updates as they learn.
name: It's time to embrace software's auto-update era | Deep Tech - CNET News

comments:
{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MjE=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'840858426', u'name': u'Karl Riehl'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-27T23:27:50+0000', u'message': u'Huh?', u'id': u'169077989790297_1983948', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T00:17:22+0000', u'message': u'Geeky stuff. I loaded a free alternative firmware for my router that has lots more features and stability. ', u'id': u'169077989790297_1984209', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'54902610', u'name': u'Rob Arms'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T02:50:27+0000', u'message': u'50mb?!?!?! Wow dude, you are ready to host a ton of users on that. Or lots of porn. lol', u'id': u'169077989790297_1984965', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T03:26:03+0000', u'message': u'If only Time Warner could run respectable DNS service.  The through put is super fast, but the DNS latency is so slow that requests intermittently fail.  Grrrrr!', u'id': u'169077989790297_1985124', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'556642634', u'name': u'Ravi Sarma'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T04:27:58+0000', u'message': u'8.8.8.8', u'id': u'169077989790297_1985407', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T04:54:16+0000', u'message': u'Yeah or 8.8.4.4. That or opendns doesn't solve it.  It's like TW has something that is disturbing traffic on port 53', u'id': u'169077989790297_1985531', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T05:30:34+0000', u'message': u'the best solution i found is to use a 2nd router.  The TW box is a modem/switch/wifi router.  I have a linksys e3000 plugged into that.  The e3 runs ddwrt with a DNS cache on it, which is pointed to opendns and google dns.  So, after any machines on my network access a site, DNS lookups are fast (cached).  I dunno, i may downgrade to the 20mb roadrunner service which doesnt seem to have that problem.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1985674', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T18:10:49+0000', u'message': u'DD-WRT is a step in the right direction! Apple is 50% FOSS. The rest, they screw up ;-) I'm trying to speed up the Linux world; progress is steady but slow. And MS evolves.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1989181', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'556642634', u'name': u'Ravi Sarma'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T21:18:57+0000', u'message': u'Hmm, if you had a GNU/Linux'ish box at home (or a Mac) you could perhaps run a simple TinyDNS cache instead. Non-cache will still be an issue, I guess.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1990452', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T21:44:05+0000', u'message': u'The router is running Linux. DDWRT is an embedded build. I can wear my pocket protector while I SSH in and be a real Linux haxx0r'', u'id': u'169077989790297_1990613', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'556642634', u'name': u'Ravi Sarma'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T22:20:52+0000', u'message': u'Yeah, I have played with DDWRT, but to be honest, never found it worth the trouble. YMMV, of course.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1990794', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-28T22:51:45+0000', u'message': u'It *is* a hassle to get right.  Selecting the right build.  The initial flash needs to be one type of build then upgrades to that another.  Still some builds just work better than others.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1990937', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-29T01:21:12+0000', u'message': u'I hope that embedded hardware will come with Linux by default at some point. I am more concerned about the desktop install. If you can't install DD-WRT, you probably shouldn't be running it. I am glad Linksys allows it. Apple has locked out Rockbox in their newer iPod hardware.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1991684', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-29T01:27:49+0000', u'message': u'It's not so much that "you can't install" it.  The install is very easy.  You just use the router's web admin "firmware upgrade" page.  You just point it at the bin file on your local disk and click "upgrade". Then it uploads the file, installs it, then reboots the router.  The biggest complexity is finding the right build to install from the DDWRT site.  too many types and versions of the builds.  Each one seems to come with it's feature fixes and bugs.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1991713', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-29T01:29:02+0000', u'message': u'Re: Linux desktop install, why not just get a mac?  All my linux friends have migrated to mac.  You get a reliable tool with great app support as well as a (mostly) real unix system underneath.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1991720', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-29T01:49:56+0000', u'message': u'I love Linux and think it is superior to the Mac in many ways. I was just speaking about how the install needs work for world domination. Here are some of the things I wrote in my book for why the Mac sucks:




* A Mac OS has more code than ever before, and a lot of it is based on free code, but it doesn’t have a repository with thousands of applications like Linux. There are several third-party efforts to provide this feature, but none are blessed or supported by Apple. The Mac comes free with iPhoto, but they really want me to buy Aperture for $159, which they tell me just added 100 new features! Apple ships a new OS every year, but you don’t get free upgrades — it costs $140 to upgrade from OS X 10.4 to 10.5.



* Many of the Mac’s UI details like how to maximize windows, and shortcut keys, are dis-similar from Windows. Linux, by contrast, feels much more natural to a Windows user. Another example: when you double-click on a picture, it loads the iPreview application that stays around even after the window displaying the picture is closed. How about just creating a window, putting the picture in that window, and having it all disappear when I close the window? I tried to change the shortcuts to match the Windows keystrokes, but their software contains bugs because it didn’t change it in all applications.



* The Mac feels like a lot of disparate pieces bolted together. The desktop widgets code has its own UI, and it doesn’t integrate well into the OS desktop. The Spaces is a clone of an old Unix feature and doesn’t implement it as well as Linux does. (For example, there is no easily discoverable way to move applications between spaces.)



* As mentioned above, the Mac doesn’t support as many of the Microsoft standards as Linux does. One of the most obvious is WMA, but it also doesn’t ship with any software that reads and writes DOC files, even though there is OpenOffice.org and other free software out there.



* It is less customizable. I cannot find a way to have the computer not go to sleep when the laptop screen is closed. The mouse speed seems too slow and you can only adjust the amount of acceleration, not the sensitivity. You neither resize the system menu bar, nor add applets like you can with Linux’s Gnome.', u'id': u'169077989790297_1991818', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-29T01:51:29+0000', u'message': u'Oh come on.  Everyone knows linux is dead. caption: www.carlosble.com
comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'Mw==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'553540611', u'name': u'Alex Hopmann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-23T19:04:09+0000', u'message': u'I'm not surprised people are having problems with it. But I do have to say many of the specific complaints seem a little naive to me. They are issues you are going to have with ANY scalable system whether you write it from scratch on raw-hardware or not. For example- Memcached values can't be bigger than 1MB. You are stuffing more than 1MB in a SINGLE value? That would createa  huge crippling overhead on the datacenter network running your app if you are retrieving multiple MBs of cached data on every request.', u'id': u'132242883499903_900839', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'553540611', u'name': u'Alex Hopmann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-23T19:04:48+0000', u'message': u'(I should clarify- by "you" I mean the author, not actually _you_) :)', u'id': u'132242883499903_900845', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'549216081', u'name': u'Yaron Y. Goland'}, u'like_count': 1, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-11-23T19:29:35+0000', u'message': u'Yeah I read the article previously and just didn't buy most of its arguments. GAE has a specific design and it's quite clear about its limitations. So if you are a round peg, it's a round hole. This guy was a square peg. Nevertheless he is exactly the kind of customer that would do well on Azure. :)', u'id': u'132242883499903_901031', u'user_likes': False}]}
description: Choosing GAE as the platform four our project is a mistake which cost I estimate in about 15000€. Considering it's been my money, it is a "bit" painful.

description: In January, 90 percent of Internet addresses were used up. Now that figure stands at 95 percent. Those in charge urge an orderly move to the roomier IPv6 realm. Read this blog post by Stephen Shankland on Deep Tech.
message:
"Major companies including Comcast, Google, and Facebook are working to adapt to an IPv6 world, but countless smaller companies have yet to begin taking the plunge."

Ho Hum.  Microsoft IT has had IPv6 and IPsec running for along time.
name: IPv4 Net addresses now 95 percent used up | Deep Tech - CNET News

description: United Parcel Service sponsored the El Toro Air Show in 1996.  this is some footage including blue angels, our booth with a 727 and package car, show fly by of our new quiet 757 (then).  It ends with some footage I shot during the show set up the day before.  Our booth was located right along the taxiway where the planes came by as they took their positions on the tarmac. I worked there in the 90s on ther Internet IT team

description: The seeds for the patent and trademark infringement suit against Google and Android were sown at Sun, but it took Oracle's financial power to bring them to fruition. Read this blog post by Stephen Shankland on Deep Tech.
message: very interesting.  Microsoft got whacked for doing very similar things to what Google is doing.  Microsoft had to pay almost 1 billion dollars and kill it's Java like product, J#. It will be interesting to see who the public sides with.
name: Why Oracle, not Sun, sued Google over Java | Deep Tech - CNET News

', u'id': u'136074966434471_1019714', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-08-14T04:56:07+0000', u'message': u'Yeah, it's a really good point. description: First ad released by the Servicemembers United Action Fund as part of its MilitaryReadiness.org campaign. More to come. Music ("Magnetic Angels") by Kerry Muzzey, used with permission, and available on iTunes. Video production by Jonathan Smith at Production Directorate.
likes: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTAwMDAwMTAxOTQ5OTcy', u'before': u'MTAwMDAwMTAxOTQ5OTcy'}}, u'data': [{u'id': u'100000101949972', u'name': u'Kirk Wilson'}]}
message: Interesting video.  Good point on DADT:  cohesion is about trust.  trust requires transparency. if you are perceived to be hiding something, it's difficult to trust you.  more at militaryreadiness.org
name: Servicemembers United Action Fund DADT Repeal Ad #1

caption: joshalot.com
comments:
{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'Mw==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'581524432', u'name': u'Bob Summersgill'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-05-26T11:15:48+0000', u'message': u'HST not LBJ of course. The blog made the error initially.

A major difference is the prior to Truman's executive order, African American service members were already serving. Segregated units had to be integrated. This caused the military to take real action to reorganize many units.

With DADT the military only needs to stop taking adverse actions against service members. No administratve or reorganizatioal action is needed. ', u'id': u'128935047119795_722343', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-05-26T20:45:21+0000', u'message': u'I see your point.  However, while the issues that need to get resolved during are different, I beleive there are still issues that will need to get resolved.  There are folks in the services who will have issues serving with gay people.  Whether we agree about the validity of those issues, they still need to be addressed.  Having homophobes with guns running around scares me.  I'm worried that there might be fragging incidents.  Identifying problematic servicemen and giving them diversity training or perhaps removing them from the situation might be necessary.', u'id': u'128935047119795_726463', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'581524432', u'name': u'Bob Summersgill'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2010-05-26T21:41:08+0000', u'message': u'Race was far more divisive when Truman signed that order. Nationally, repeal of DADT has support of 75%. For younger people, it is higher. Most service members are younger, and much less homophobic than the brass. They are far, far, less homophobic than the troops in Truman's day were racist. 

Military codes of conduct are quite sufficient to handle this as is.', u'id': u'128935047119795_726910', u'user_likes': False}]}

comments: {u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'Nw==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-26T08:27:55+0000', u'message': u'Will it be improved over time, or weakened?', u'id': u'222592237294_8869945', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-26T08:40:23+0000', u'message': u'Hmm.  well, i guess that depends on who gets elected.  Though the current bull is so far from what we were hoping for, it's painful to imagine it getting weakened.', u'id': u'222592237294_8870101', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-26T17:15:42+0000', u'message': u'Painful to imagine, yes.  But likely, given the controlling influence of big money.', u'id': u'222592237294_8881545', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'500010460', u'name': u'Mike Belshe'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-27T06:04:47+0000', u'message': u'Incrementally backward, actually.  The right solution would have enabled health insurers to work cross state lines; without that, we've got monopolies, high premiums, and reduced benefits.', u'id': u'222592237294_8899539', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-27T07:19:34+0000', u'message': u'Um, the Senate bill does allow insurance to be sold across state lines.  That's one of the major flaws, as it eliminates protections that some states offer.  Like Delaware for credit cards.', u'id': u'222592237294_8900618', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1344780533', u'name': u'Randall Gellens'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-27T07:20:34+0000', u'message': u'The bill should have government-provided basic coverage, with anyone and any company free to purchase additional coverage.  No mandates, no middlemen, no overhead.', u'id': u'222592237294_8900633', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'500010460', u'name': u'Mike Belshe'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-27T10:38:51+0000', u'message': u'Randall - we'll see how it plays out when merged reconciled with the House.  Gov't insurance has vastly more overhead than private insurance.  You should read up on Medicare overhead and particularly fraud.   Prior to Obama's spending spree this year,  Medicare has been traditionally one of the two largest single federal line items - at about 25% of total US spending annually.  You think covering 20% of Americans (healthcare only) is efficiently covered by 25% of the TOTAL Federal budget?  Strange.  And we didn't even discuss Medicaid or the other gov't run healthcare programs that already exist.', u'id': u'222592237294_8903338', u'user_likes': False}]}

I want to thank my friend Josh Cohen for finding this video interview of Matthew Shepard and his then boyfriend from college.  Watching it reminds me to not take a single day for granted, nor any opportunity to make the world a better place for the next generation of LGBT kids.

Yours in the united stand for equality,

+ Phil

caption: www.huffingtonpost.com
comments:
{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTA=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'500010460', u'name': u'Mike Belshe'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-11T22:37:33+0000', u'message': u'There isn't really anything to impeach him for, but his performance has been mind-numbingly awful.  If I could go change my vote, McCain would have it.
', u'id': u'367507520318_9025425', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T00:31:41+0000', u'message': u'If the Republicans had nominated a white constitutional law professor, the media would have slammed him as a clueless elite out of touch with reality. Obama got a different treatment.', u'id': u'367507520318_9029106', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T00:48:27+0000', u'message': u'I have low expectations from our government no matter who's in charge.  However, I'm content enough, at this early stage in Obama's first term, with the progress on issues and unwinding some of the messes he inherited.  Among other things, we're actually having a health care reform debate, we've started actually talking to folks like Iran instead of provoking them "Axis of Evil!", the Matthew Shepard federal hate crimes law has been signed into law, the legislature is moving forward to give domestic partner benefits to govt employees...  I don't believe these things would be happening if McCain was elected.  ', u'id': u'367507520318_9029596', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T04:43:52+0000', u'message': u'The best way to be happy with Obama is to lower your expectations. If "having a healthcare debate" is more important than "passing legislation that will lower costs and improve quality", then you can be satisfied with the progress.

The Republican party's best community organizer is Obama!', u'id': u'367507520318_9036069', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T04:48:26+0000', u'message': u'WIth Obama, at least things are moving in the right direction.  The meat of the bill is ultimately negotiated by the legislature, so the efficacy of the final bill is more than just his responsibility.  I would expect that health care reform, especially given people's strong feelings on it, will take a big chunk of time to come to agreement on in order to pass something into law.  The President sets the agenda, and I like what he's doing.
', u'id': u'367507520318_9036171', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T05:12:50+0000', u'message': u'You sound more interested in intentions than results.', u'id': u'367507520318_9036678', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T06:57:24+0000', u'message': u'why?', u'id': u'367507520318_9038657', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T09:09:08+0000', u'message': u'Because you speak of "hard feelings" rather than "good policies." And you say it is fine that Obama is delegating the details of the legislation to Congress.

You either don't care about whether the effort will achieve the announced goals, or you know the results won't be good, so are choosing to ignore that aspect.

The only bipartisanship in DC is in opposition to Obama's policies! McCain would do better, as Bush did.', u'id': u'367507520318_9040937', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'500010460', u'name': u'Mike Belshe'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-12T15:43:19+0000', u'message': u'Josh, Check this out.  http://www.gpoaccess.gov/usbudget/fy10/pdf/budget/summary.pdf

Bush was a bad spender - he racked up a $459B deficit.  In this document (prepared by the Obama administration!)  Obama states pulicly that he is planning to rack up deficits of $1,509B this year, $1,178B next year, then $1,033B, $757B, $734B, $791B, $811B, $878B, and upward from there....  In other words, on a GOOD year, Obama is 2x WORSE than Bush!

This is gross financial irresponsibility.  This isn't just TARP.  This is pure Obama.  

At the same time, if he gets his way, the economy will be slammed with the single biggest tax increase ever! (healthcare)

At the same time, he wants to deal with climate change, that is good.  But is he really planning to pay for the chinese to clean up their act?  The only tax increase bigger than healthcare could be this one!

But what about an energy policy?  Does Obama have a plan?  Nope.  How about job growth, do we have that?  Nope!

How about getting us out of the middle east?  Is he doing that?  Nope!  Shit - that was the reason I voted for him!  He wants to do Bush-round-2, this time in Afghanistan.

Obama is a total disaster of financial irresponsibility, forgotten promises, and not even addressing our nation's basic needs.', u'id': u'367507520318_9050850', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-12-13T16:21:49+0000', u'message': u'Mike, I'm impressed with your open-mindedness.

Many people are Democrats first and Americans second  and get so caught up in wanting to believe in Obama that they rationalize even his bad decisions. It is a sad pseudo-religion with Obama as the Messiah.

Wasn't Tiger Woods the model of a perfect family man until 2 weeks ago? The image of Obama was equally as whitewashed.', u'id': u'367507520318_9090628', u'user_likes': False}]}

comments:
{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MTQ=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'500010460', u'name': u'Mike Belshe'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-02T21:10:09+0000', u'message': u'Sure, I get it.  Some people kill because they hate some group.  The guy is in jail for 20yrs, which seems pretty appropriate to me.  Why do we need hate crime legislation?  He's already in jail.  The system worked.  Whether he kills because he hates, because his targets are easy, because he's violent, because he's stupid, or all of the above, the law worked.   I don't really care if we have hate legislation or not.  If it makes some groups of people feel better to have it, then I'm not really against it either, but to me it's just redundant law.', u'id': u'91725708082_1708598', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'504486165', u'name': u'German Munoz'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-02T21:18:35+0000', u'message': u'Hmmm, don't really mean I like that "gays are easy targets:. Sounds kind of morbid. I support calling out this issue. =)', u'id': u'91725708082_1708678', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'788708648', u'name': u'Deborah Kerman'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-02T23:15:48+0000', u'message': u'@Mike:  I think hate crimes are different b/c they're not just crimes against an individual, they are also attacking a whole group of people.  e.g., after 9/11 people attacked Muslims, or even just people who appeared to be Muslims.  That hurt all Muslims, in addition to the people who were actually attacked.  The other Muslims weren't harmed in the same way of course, but they were still harmed.  At least, that's my view. :)', u'id': u'91725708082_1709718', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-03T01:03:56+0000', u'message': u'@Deborah: The people who didn't get murdered didn't get murdered.

This law puts certain victims above other victims.

It also gets the government involved in reading thoughts.', u'id': u'91725708082_1710543', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'556642634', u'name': u'Ravi Sarma'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-03T03:16:36+0000', u'message': u'What is the theory and framework of justice? Retributive? Is the choice of penalty based on its value as a deterrent? If the idea is to impose punishment calibrated to societal moral codes and goals a hate crime ranks higher on the negative scale than say a crime of passion. Society then decides that the punishment has to fit the extent to which the perpetrator is found immoral. I am not saying I endorse such a framework, but I can see the validity of such a justification. The law does take intent into account in various instances.', u'id': u'91725708082_1711664', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'788708648', u'name': u'Deborah Kerman'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-03T19:18:31+0000', u'message': u'yeah, exactly -- motive counts.  and if someone says "I killed him b/c he was gay" or some such, it's pretty easy to figure out motive.  it doesn't distinguish victims -- not every murder of someone who happens to be gay is a hate crime.', u'id': u'91725708082_1719022', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'655094120', u'name': u'Chris Newman'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-04T06:51:03+0000', u'message': u'@Mike: Why do we make a distinction between first degree murder and manslaughter?  Because the former is more likely to be repeated, thus a more serious punishment is merited.  A criminal who commits a hate crime is likely to repeat that crime on someone else in the target class in the future.  So again, that means the punishment should be more serious to protect society.', u'id': u'91725708082_1725206', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'500010460', u'name': u'Mike Belshe'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-04T16:45:03+0000', u'message': u'@Chris - First degree vs Second degree murder already covers hate motives as well as other motives.  I never said we shouldn't consider motive, we absolutely should, and we already do.  Hate crime legislation is redundant with existing law.  As Keith also intelligently pointed out, Hate Crime legislation gives some victims less justice than others, which is wrong.  It is not more serious to kill homosexual people than heterosexual people.', u'id': u'91725708082_1730492', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-04T21:02:48+0000', u'message': u'@mike:  " It is not more serious to kill homosexual people than heterosexual people."
Sure, if you throw a rock in the air and it kills a gay, heterosexual, christian, black person, or woman, its all the same.
However, if you seek out someone because they are a member of a certain persecuted group, it is more serious.  You're not really attacking that person, or even based on your own passion for that persion.  You're attacking a protected class of people.  
In both the case i describe as well as the Matt Shepard case, they were selected because they were gay.  in both cases, the killers cited the victims sexuaity and an alledged sexual advance as a motive for their murder.

I can understand the libertarian view that the government shouldnt be imposing laws like this.  However, consider that whats happening here is that LGBT is being aded to an existing list of protected classes.  So, being opposed to any hate crimes laws is a reasonable position (though its not one i share; i be', u'id': u'91725708082_1734156', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-04T21:04:47+0000', u'message': u'hmm is there a limit on length here or am i just hitting some IE8 bug?  
Continuing:
So, being opposed to any hate crimes laws is a reasonable position (though its not one i share; i believe they are necesary).  However, whats going on here is the inclusion of LGBT in an existing model.

assuming that we *do* have hate crimes laws, are you oppsed to adding LGBT alongside, race, sex, religion, etc?', u'id': u'91725708082_1734192', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-04T22:47:39+0000', u'message': u'It isn't clear that federal hate crime legislation already exists. I found a quote from star tribune:

"The legislation, also known as the Matthew Shepard Act, would assist federal officials in their prosecution of hate crimes that target victims because of race, color, religion, national origin, gender, sexual orientation, sexual identity or disability."', u'id': u'91725708082_1735626', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-07T01:48:49+0000', u'message': u'@keith: Have a look at: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Shepard_Act

States:
The Matthew Shepard Act (officially, the Local Law Enforcement Hate Crimes Prevention Act of 2007 or LLEHCPA), H.R. 1592 was a proposed federal bill that would expand the 1969 United States federal hate-crime law to include crimes motivated by a victim's actual or perceived gender, sexual orientation, gender identity, or disability.', u'id': u'91725708082_1771897', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-07T06:36:56+0000', u'message': u'@josh: I don't trust wikipedia when it comes to politics. And when I click on the link for HR 1592, it mentions many more categories of hate crimes.

I googled some more and found that HRC agrees with me!

http://www.hrc.org/laws_and_elections/5660.htm

BTW, I find it Orwellian that the law is named after someone whose perps received life sentences!', u'id': u'91725708082_1774654', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'810866601', u'name': u'Keith Curtis'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-05-07T06:37:23+0000', u'message': u'BTW, I find it Orwellian that the law is named after someone whose perps received life sentences!', u'id': u'91725708082_1774657', u'user_likes': False}]}

{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'MjM=', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'1210203560', u'name': u'Kip Cook'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T17:53:06+0000', u'message': u'#14 explains Brian. He laughs more than anyone I have ever met. Thanks for the warning on #11. I'll make sure to never pay you a surprise visit. ;-)', u'id': u'47982672547_627511', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T17:58:33+0000', u'message': u'lol....yea.  Fortunately, not many people just drop in saying "well I happened to be in the neighborhood and  I thought I'd drop in".', u'id': u'47982672547_627563', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1210203560', u'name': u'Kip Cook'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T17:59:17+0000', u'message': u'I bet they will now.. HA!', u'id': u'47982672547_627571', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1514314900', u'name': u'Nicola Mccann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:14:40+0000', u'message': u'#26.  Old friends that have been out of touch still consider me one of their all time favorite people....', u'id': u'47982672547_627681', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:14:47+0000', u'message': u'It gave me up when the muffler went and later the radiator.  I was going to give it to charity but oddly enough a friend bought it from me and fixed it up and drove it another year or so before it finally died.  I upgraded from the Storm to a BMW....so I really need to keep this car for at least twice as long as the storm.', u'id': u'47982672547_627683', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1514314900', u'name': u'Nicola Mccann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:18:45+0000', u'message': u'Wasn't that storm a magnet for breakins in new brunswick?', u'id': u'47982672547_627716', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:19:07+0000', u'message': u'back atcha Nikki....you are one of the people whose laugh I found infectious.  I miss the days of sitting on the porch on Freeman St in NB drinking coffee with whipped cream and smoking cigs....also miss the poker games and trips to Oz bar in NB on Wednesdays (My boss at IBM always wondered why I came into work so late on Thurs morns).', u'id': u'47982672547_627717', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:20:13+0000', u'message': u'With no driver's side window on the storm for a long time, not really a break-in....just reach in and take what you want.  That and the cat who lived in it when it was parked on the street.', u'id': u'47982672547_627723', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:22:31+0000', u'message': u'at roughly 5K miles a year, I should be able to get my money's worth on it.  And that included a road trip from Atlanta to Maine to Quebec to Toronto to Pittsburg and back to Atlanta.', u'id': u'47982672547_627743', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1514314900', u'name': u'Nicola Mccann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:29:08+0000', u'message': u'Couldn't you have been more OCD when we lived together?  Like doing dishes???  and I seem to recall one time they dumped everything out of your glove compartment and didn't take a thing!!!', u'id': u'47982672547_627794', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:34:08+0000', u'message': u'Nothing to take....The best was when a fight broke out in front of the house and someone got thrown up on my car, denting the hood with their body and cracking the windshield with their head.  The blood got cleaned off quickly but it took me a few years to replace the windshield.', u'id': u'47982672547_627836', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1514314900', u'name': u'Nicola Mccann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:37:05+0000', u'message': u'I seem to recall you driving on 287 in a snow storm...with no ability to see out of the windshield...and no driver side window!!', u'id': u'47982672547_627866', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1514314900', u'name': u'Nicola Mccann'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:37:20+0000', u'message': u'Good times.', u'id': u'47982672547_627868', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T18:48:55+0000', u'message': u'Yea....the driver's side window got broken when I was working for Will Lloyd as a laborer.  Someone backed into my parked car when the window was down so it got broken.  She had no insurance so I agreed to just let her pay me and she never did.  I was too poor (read cheap) for a long time to fix it and had to bundle up for the long drive from NB to IBM in Parsippany in the winter.  It finally got fixed when I moved to Atlanta but the windshield stayed cracked for another few years.  The worst was when I got into an accident on 287 heading to work and the airbag deployed.  I had just opened my "Big One" Dunkin Donuts coffee so I ended up with hot coffee burns all over me.  And the airbag never got replaced.  I just folded it back up and tucked it into the steerin wheel an glued the steering wheel back shut.   Good times indeed!', u'id': u'47982672547_627967', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1210203560', u'name': u'Kip Cook'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T19:51:53+0000', u'message': u'Damn... Cheap doesn't do you justice.. LOL', u'id': u'47982672547_628508', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1119180224', u'name': u'Carolyn Roach Busby'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T20:14:02+0000', u'message': u'11. You live like 3 miles from me, right? <grabs camera>   ;-)', u'id': u'47982672547_628748', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T20:41:49+0000', u'message': u'Yea....but you'll never get past the huge gates at the entrance of the neighborhood.', u'id': u'47982672547_629068', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1119180224', u'name': u'Carolyn Roach Busby'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T20:43:18+0000', u'message': u'I'm stealthy.  :-P', u'id': u'47982672547_629086', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'619639230', u'name': u"Vickey Podell O'Connor"}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-29T21:16:09+0000', u'message': u'Ahhh...D&D and you and coffee...I remember it well except then you smoked!  So happy you gave it up!', u'id': u'47982672547_629427', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2009-01-30T09:30:09+0000', u'message': u'yo.  shout out to my fellow dunkin donuts colleague!
gimmie an egg and bacon crossanwich!', u'id': u'47982672547_633472', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'1209610267', u'name': u'Bonnie Mason'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': False, u'created_time': u'2009-01-30T16:50:45+0000', u'message': u'I remember your tatoo...  I love Dave Matthews.. Congratulations on not smoking anymore - alot of people can't break that awful habit!...  I bet your neighbors love you at night!  LOL', u'id': u'47982672547_635683', u'user_likes': False}]}

{u'paging': {u'cursors': {u'after': u'NQ==', u'before': u'MQ=='}}, u'data': [{u'from': {u'id': u'1030235866', u'name': u'John DeLuca'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2008-12-08T22:37:12+0000', u'message': u'It was good seeing you', u'id': u'52432276784_404836', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'792709844', u'name': u'Michael Callahan'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2008-12-08T22:38:40+0000', u'message': u'You too. I finally broke down and joined this thing. Is everyone in the world on here? I just friended Brian. Tell him not to get all sidditty with me! 

We are long overdue for catch-up, dude!', u'id': u'52432276784_404839', u'user_likes': False}, {u'from': {u'id': u'569966468', u'name': u'Josh Cohen'}, u'like_count': 0, u'can_remove': True, u'created_time': u'2008-12-08T23:03:42+0000', u'message': u'i just took the train up from DC to catch my flight.  Was here for Thanksgiving with the family, then went to Denver for work, then to DC for a conference.  Conference ended today.  Trained it up from DC to newark and now on the plane waiting to taxi.
The flight attendants dont know that I am on my net connection.
